    "title": "Bread sauce",
    "subtitle": "Spiced infused milk, thickened with white bread",
    "excerpt": "Whole milk infused with a clove-studded onion and bay, then thickened with fresh white breadcrumbs. The traditional British accompaniment to roast turkey, chicken, and game.",
    "sourceNotes": "Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136. Bread sauce for roast chicken and turkey.\n\nEliza Acton, Modern Cookery for Private Families (1845). Bread sauce methods.",
    "body": {
      "type": "doc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Bread sauce is an unusual preparation by modern standards: bread as a thickener for a spiced milk sauce. It works because the breadcrumbs soften completely into the milk, producing a texture that is creamy and rich without using cream. The flavour comes entirely from the infusing stage: a long, slow infusion is what separates bread sauce from a glass of warm milk with bread in it.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
