        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Infuse and thicken",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "Stud",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpedg44p0000zov49lv5ec9c"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " the onion halves with the cloves by pressing them into the cut surface. Place in a medium saucepan with the milk, bay leaves, and peppercorns.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Heat over very low heat until just below simmering point. ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "Infuse",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpsojcll000014v4ageg08qp"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " for 30 minutes, keeping the milk just below the boil. Do not rush this step.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Remove the onion, bay leaves, and peppercorns. Add the breadcrumbs and butter. Stir over low heat for 10 minutes until the breadcrumbs have absorbed the milk and the sauce is thick and creamy. Grate in the nutmeg generously. Add the cream if using. Season with salt. Serve immediately, or keep warm with a lid on, stirring occasionally.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "fix": "Add more breadcrumbs in small amounts, stirring and allowing each addition to absorb before adding the next. The sauce should be thick enough to hold a soft mound.",
                "cause": "Not enough breadcrumbs, or the infusion time was too short so the milk was cold when the bread was added.",
                "symptom": "The sauce is thin and runny"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Six cloves for 500 ml of milk is about right. The clove flavour is background warmth, not dominant. Reduce to 4 next time.",
                "cause": "Too many cloves, or the infusion went on too long.",
                "symptom": "The sauce has a harsh clove taste"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Lay a disc of greaseproof paper directly on the surface, or stir every few minutes to prevent skin formation.",
                "cause": "Exposed milk surface cooling and forming a protein skin.",
                "symptom": "The sauce has a skin forming on top while being kept warm"
              },
              {
                "fix": "The 30-minute infusion is the minimum. Day-old bread absorbs milk more efficiently and adds a slightly more flavourful starch.",
                "cause": "Insufficient infusing time, or the bread was too fresh and soft.",
                "symptom": "The sauce tastes flat and insipid"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Variations",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Add 2 tablespoons of double cream at the end for a richer sauce. A pinch of mace alongside the nutmeg gives a more complex spice note. Some older recipes add a tablespoon of dry sherry at the end.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Bread sauce is a medieval British preparation. Bread as a thickener fell out of fashion across European cooking long ago, but this sauce survived in Britain. Victorian cookery writer Mrs Beeton describes it as essential for roast fowl. It remains the traditional accompaniment to roast chicken, turkey, and game birds, and has survived partly through habit and partly because it works so well as a sauce.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
